 <br>
I've reviewed your paper, its very interesting.  I have a few points to share below.  Enjoy!<br>
 <br>
--William Mook<br>
 <br>
 <br>
(1) Radiation Release -   You assume 10 people die for every launch of an Orion spacecraft.  You give things in terms of rads per launch, and then assume 100,000 rads per launch which translates to 10 people, if I read your paper right.  However, what is the total yeild (number of explosions x yeild per explosion) for each launch?  What is the total number of grams of radioactive material released?  What is the total number of grams of payload to space?<br>
 <br>
(2) EMP Effects -  Do you distinguish between prompt HEMP and secondary EMP effects?  If so, how?  I didn't see it in your discussion, nor in your program source code.  What are the effects of thrust structure on these?  Both in terms of directed plasma burst (as opposed to isotropic burst) and in terms of thrust strructure effects?<br>
 <br>
You've clearly done a valiant bit of research, and I commend you on it.  However, I have a few comments to make on some of your conclusions about the negative effects of a nuclear pulse rocket launch;<br>
 <br>
(1) Microfission triggers for larger fusion blasts - Reduce long-term radiation release by using microfission to trigger small fusion blasts.  This works as follows; use ICF techniques with fissile fuels not fusion, to produce very small fission blasts.  Use these fission blasts to initiate fusion blasts some 1000x larger.  Thus, fissile releases are 1/1000th that of an all fission system with the same total yeild.  Rationale: Nuclear explosions have traditionally used chemical explosives to compress sub-critical fissile material to critical densities.  The smallest possible explosion one can efficiently achieve is determined in part by the greatest density one achieves at peak compression.  Chemical explosives have limited enthalpy.  Thus, even with shock waves that concentrate compressive energy spherically, density multiples of 3 are about the limit that can be attained.  This places a lower limit on efficient yeild to about 10 kt or so.  Anything smaller, using traditional nuclear explosive designs doesn't reduce the amount of fissile material used and the total long-term radioactive materials released.  Non-chemical compression of fissile fuels however have the potential to achieves higher densities at peak compression, and thus have the potential to reduce efficient minimum yeilds to less than 1 kt.  In fact, researchers at University of Pennsylvania and USAF Phillips labs, along with CERN, have performed research that indicates an anti-proton boosted microfission device using theta-pinch type compression of the fissile fuel, or any of the other methods of igniting an inertial confinement fusion process can attain efficient burnup of a fissile fuel with as little at 2 tons (no k!) of TNT equivalent yeild.  This is an extraordinarily small amount of fissile material.  Please note the anti-protons are held in Penning traps, as protons, not anti-matter.  Further, the anti-protons are used as a catalyst to increase neutron yeild of the fissile fuels. Anti-protons in this design are not used to detonate the fissile material or power the compression process.  Inertial confinement fusion technologies achieve far far higher pressures than chemical explosions can achieve and can achieve densities high enough to produce fissile explosions in the 20 ton range without antiproton catalysts.  The resulting fissile explosion in both cases is highly concentrated and easily exceeds the Lawson Criterion for self-propagating fusion reaction.  It should therefore be possible to <br>
     (a) Use Inertial Confinement Fusion Technology - to achieve very small yeild fissile bomblets with high burnup;<br>
     (b) Use the energy from the fissile bomblet to initiate a fusion explosion with a 1000:1 multiple;<br>
     (c) use the fusion explosion to power a nuclear pulse rocket;<br>
In this way it should be possible to reduce release of long-term fissile pollution from nuclear pulse rocket launches to levels 1/1000th  the levels assumed for an all fission system;<br>
 <br>
(2) Shape pusher plate to limit EMP effects - EMP effects can be reduced or eliminated by reducing and directing gamma ray emissions.  If you haven't already, I suggest you read <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.fas.org/nuke/intro/nuke/emp.htm">www.fas.org/nuke/intro/nuke/emp.htm</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END-->  which introduces some of the physics (without math unfortunately) of HEMP and MHD-EMP effects.  Gamma rays scattered from the atmosphere at altitudes between 20 km and 40 km easily dislodge electrons from the nuclei of air molecules.  At higher densities the gammas lose too much energy with distance by scattering to create broad EMP effects.  At lower densities, the gammas don't encounter enough molecules per cubic meter to create powerful EMP effects.  The intensity of gamma rays falls off as the inverse square of the distance from the explosive center.  The gamma ray intensity determines the percentage of air molecules ionized.  Within a certain range all the air molecules are ionized - which depends on air density yeild, scattering cross section, and so forth.  All air molecules within this sphere are essentially ionized simultaneously, and electrons are scattered away from the explosive center.  This prompt scattering causes a huge charge to build up around the explosive center, which halts the expansion of the electron cloud.  All electrons stop essentially at the same time.  Since the acceleration of electrical charges radiates away energy, this scattering followed by halting, produces the first 10 ns EMP pulse.  Of course, now, the electrons separated from their nuclei, come back toward the explosive center, and in the process are effected by the magnetic field of Earth.  This is the HEMP effect, lasting many hundreds of microseconds.  The nuclei of the air molecules themselves are not uneffected by this.  These nuclei are also affected by the expansion of the plasma around the explosive center.  This produces the longer lasting MHD-EMP effects.  To the extent the pusher plate absorbs or limits gamma radiation, the plate reduces EMP effects in the 'shaded' region.  This shaded region is a function of plate shape, as well as plate diameter versus standoff distance.  The ability of plates, flat curved or otherwise, to withstand repeated impacts from repeated nuclear explosions, is something that has not been openly analysed in the engineering literature.  When two bodies impinge on one another (billiard balls, hammer and steel, golf club and ball, plasma burst and steel) the contact is of extremely short duration and the contact forces are very large in magnitude.  These are called impacts.  In the general case of impact between two bodies the area under the curve is the most important property.  The coefficient of restitution is the most important measure.  It tells how two bodies rebound, and how much is absorbed by each body.  This is an interesting place to start.  You know what the yeild of the nuclear explosion is.  You know the mass of the nuclear device.  You know the percentage of the total energy that goes into the explosive expansion of the nuclear device.  From this, and a few other fundamentals, you can figure what the coefficient of restitution is for the plasma pulse and the plate.  From that you can determine the impact effects.  From this you can engineer the plate (within broad limits).  My analysis indicates you can explode nuclear pulse units inside a hemispheric or even parabolic thrust structure and have the structure survive.  This is quite different than a rocket engine that has a converging and diverging section between the combustion chamber and the nozzle.  Essentially, what we are doing, since the expanding plasma pulse is already supersonic, is operating the tail end of a nozzle - of varying efficiencies.  While its true that very large nozzles (one can write a function that goes from a very small nozzle (essentially a plate) the standoff distance away, to a very large nozzle whose radius is the standoff distance) are very heavy, its also true that percentage of total yeild captured for thrust also is very large - so Thrust to Weight ratio is not as adversely affected as one might expect.  If one adds mass to the bomb, without increasing yeild, thrust can be increased since;<br>
 <br>
                         F = ma which by first law of Calculus can be rewritten; F= mdot * Ve <br>
                         E = 1/2 * m Ve^2  which differentiates to;  Power = 1/2 * mdot * Ve^2<br>
 <br>
so thrust and power are related by;<br>
 <br>
                        F = 2*Power * Ve<br>
 <br>
and mass flow rate and power are related by;<br>
 <br>
                       mdot = 2 * Power<br>
 <br>
mdot = mass flow rate in kg/sec<br>
Power = watts = joules/sec<br>
E = energy, joules<br>
m = mass, kg<br>
F = Force, Newtons<br>
Ve= effective exhaust velocity, m/sec<br>
 <br>
The yeild times the pulse rate gives the average power level.  The mass flow rate is given by the bomb mass times the pulse rate.  So, thrust can be increased as thrust structure increases by increasing the size of the bomblet.  <br>
 <br>
This has two important effects on EMP.  (a) Sheilding of gamma rays by large enclosing thrust structure, (b) absorbing gamma burst within a larger inert bomb structure - reducing and eliminating EMP effects.<br>
 <br>
(3) Matching Isp to mission needs further minimizes radioactive release - Of course, one gets really big payloads by packing inert material around bomblets, if limited to 20 kT equivalent yields!  But, payload no larger than our largest ships.  The largest superfreighter masses about 500,000 metric tons.  The largest ship ever planned is the Freedom Ship, massing about 4.5 million tons.  So, a 1 million ton payload to space, while large, isn't beyond feasibility.<br>
 <br>
While propellant mass increases, radiation can actually decrease with this process.  In terms of radiation release, radiation release is a function of total yeild - total energy released by fissile products.  By controlling the average exhaust energy of the reaction products, one can minimize this yeild.<br>
 <br>
The speed of a rocket propelled projectile is given by the rocket equation;<br>
 <br>
    Vf = Ve * LN(1/(1-u))<br>
 <br>
Where Vf = final velocity of a single stage rocket - m/sec<br>
           Ve = exhaust velocity of a rocket's engine - m/sec<br>
           LN( = natural log function.<br>
           u = propellant fraction<br>
 <br>
Rewrite this as;<br>
 <br>
      u = 1 - 1/EXP(Vf/Ve)<br>
 <br>
Total energy needed to operate a rocket is given by;<br>
 <br>
       E = 1/2 * m * Ve^2<br>
 <br>
Where m is the mass of the rocket's propellant in kg,<br>
          Ve = exhaust velocity in m/sec<br>
         E = energy in joules<br>
 <br>
If one takes a rocket of any size (say 1 unit) and plots total energy versus exhaust velocity to achieve a given velocity - say escape velocity of Earth (11km/sec) - one finds that you have a minimum energy in the exhausted gases when Ve~Vf.  The actual relation depends on the amount of energy lost as heat in the gases, or used to energize expanding plasmas in directions tangential to the direction of thrust, and so forth - which is a function of thrust structure shape and explosive plasma shape.  <br>
 <br>
You end up with a Ve=11,000 m/sec and an Isp of about 1,200 sec - (since Ve = Isp * g0, where g0=9.82 m/sec/sec) for an Earth escape mission, as being the range for minimum energy - and thus minimal yeild release.<br>
 <br>
(4) Nuclear pulse systems can return very large payloads to Earth - My analysis indicates that a few kg of fissile materials can be divided into many hundreds of separate triggers which can be used to detonate many hundreds of tonnes of fusion materials.  These fusion materials can be used to energize several billions of tonnes of inert materials (such as silica) to return several billions of tons of elemental materials to Earth from the asteroid belt.  <br>
 <br>
(5) Mining releases large quantities of radon gases which have long term radiological consequences - The mining and burning of coal releases hundreds of kg of radon into the environment.  The mining and reduction of iron to steel releases similar quantities of radiological materials.  In fact, any mining operation, whether strip mining or deep mining, releases vast quantities of radioactive radon gas.  <br>
 <br>
(6) Increasing material standards of living require increased quantities of raw materials - Rising living standards require greater amounts of raw materials be consumed.  To maintain the current global population requires 11x the current levels of production of most materials.  If these materials are extracted from the Earth's crust and refined on Earth, these materials will result in vast increases in the radiological releases assuming sufficient materials exist on Earth.<br>
 <br>
(7) Retrieving materials from deep space reduces the radiological burden of high standards of living on Earth - Nuclear pulse reduces the cost of space travel about 1,000 fold.  Nuclear pulse increases the range of space travel from cislunar space to entire solar system access.  Nuclear pulse increases payloads from hundreds of tons per year range to ten billion tons per year range.  This is on par with what is required by humanity.  Returning 10 billion tons of elemental materials to Earth with the release of less than a kg of fissile material into the Earth's biosphere will actually reduce the radiological release into Earth's biosphere from human activity.<br>
 <br>
 <br>
CONCLUSIONS:<br>
 <br>
The number of deaths per launch of a 3,000 ton ship you examined, is less than 1/100th of a person using microfission as a trigger to a larger fusion blast;<br>
 <br>
The number of deaths per launch of a 1 million ton payload to the asteroid belt is less than 1 person optimizing Isp for Earth launch to further minimize total yeild;<br>
 <br>
The amount of material elemental returned to Earth per launch of 1 million ton payload to the asteroids exceeds 10 billion tons;<br>
 <br>
This material when used to displace current mining and refining operations on Earth results in the savings of over 1,000 lives per year;<br>
 <br>
*NOTES: Energy extraction is unique exception to the harvest cycle described above to accelerate the radiological benefits of nuclear pulse launches.  We can launch solar power satellites to orbit directly from Earth with large nuclear pulse ships at far lower costs than with chemical rockets.  These powersats beam energy to Earth to displace the use of fossil fuels (gas, oil, coal) and nuclear fuels.  Thus, the reductions in radiological release by shutting down nuclear plants, and to a lesser extent, coal mining operations as well as oil and gas drilling operations on Earth, provide a big radiological advantage very quickly.  <br>
 <br>
**NOTES: The global installed energy base for electrical utilities is approximately 4 trillion watts.  The energy usage worldwide is about 5x this, or 20 trillion watts.  The energy requirement for the entire world to use energy at the rate of the average US citizen, would be around 220 trillion watts.  So, this places a range to operate within for a solar powersat based energy net &quot;enernet&quot;.  By requiring that any new entity produce power at 80% the cost of existing sources, we can also set a range of costs needed to be met for powersats including lift capacity. <br>
 <br>
***NOTES: Once lower energy and raw material costs are achieved from space based assets and resources, market penetration will occur naturally, beamed energy from space, and materials delivered from space, will be easily delivered anywhere they're needed, and since there is savings in using the systems, this will result in massive economic growth (assuming no rise in taxes), <br>
 <br>
****NOTES:  Allowing a sustainable 7% per year - there's a doubling every 10 years.  Assuming a starting point 1% of current global demand, and growth to 11x current demand, is 1100x the starting point, which will take 103 years at 7% average annualized growth; assuming 14% annualized growth (as achieved in Europe and Japan following WWII) and a reduction in material requirements to half that used today through re-engineering of products for improved efficiency, we have 550x the starting point which will take 48 years at 14% annualized growth.  This gives us a time period which the nuclear pulse ships will operate to transform life on Earth - from 2050 to 2105.<br>
 <br>
vNOTES:  Current value of global economy is $40 trillion according to CIA sources.  The total value of global energy and extraction industry is $3 trillion according to DOE and USGS sources.  Global population is about 6,500 million.  US population is 280 million.    US accounts for 1/4 of the first number and 1/3 of the second number.  Thus, the world of 2050-2100 time frame will be create about $285 trillion per year and the materials and energy used will be valued at about $33 trillion.<br>
 <br>
v*NOTES: A $30 billion starting point, and a $33 trillion end point over a 48 or 103 year period, will give you a rate of return, and by applying a discount rate of 40% for early R&amp;D, and 28% for mature R&amp;D, and 14% for operating profit returns - will give you the amount that can be invested in nuclear pulse rockets and their payloads over this time period.<br>
 <br>
v**NOTES:  Not only do nuclear pulse rockets operated in this way have the potential to save lives by reducing overall radiological release, they also save lives by improving living standards throughout the world, as well as create jobs, reduce political turmoil, and increase economic and political stability.<br>
